Bergsland only discusses object pronouns, treating the subject pronouns as only indexation. However, he then gives examples where "object" pronouns can be used as subjects (along with indexation): for emphasis, and for coordination. We thus treat the free pronouns as not just object pronouns but subject as well, although they are rarely used in the subject role.

In the case of a 3pl>3pl scenario, it becomes ambiguous what ni- is marking (pl subject or pl object), and we have not encoded this scenario twice, once for each interpretation. The claim that 3pl A always has this morpheme covers 3pl>3pl as well.

A small number of verbs take mixed paradigms of A and B prefixes, sometimes also with elements from the set C prefixes, that are normally used for possession. It is not clear if both transitive and intransitive verbs can have these “merged” paradigms, we could only find examples of intransitive verbs in the grammar. There is also mention of elements of the D possessive set being able to participate in these merged paradigms, but we have found no example of this whatsoever in the grammar. Given that the A, B and C paradigms have no overlap of forms for any person, the alignment patterns are not greatly changed, even if these merged paradigms are used (either with intransitive or transitive verbs). The effect of a merged paradigm would be a tripartite alignment instead of accusative for a few persons for these particular verbs. So, we are not including these merged paradigms explicitly in our coding.

This class may have at one point been mostly verbs in which the S is an undergoer, and the source says that these form the core of this class. However, there are many exceptions to this, including very basic verbs like 'run', 'meet', 'catch', and 'swim'. Consequently, we have considered this class to fall into the <any> category in terms of Exemplar, rather than <non-exemplar>. The Set B prefixes are also used with transitive verbs where the subject lacks control, e.g. experiencer verbs. Because we have not encoded experiencer verbs in this database, the ClassB transitive verbs do not appear in this database.
